Note:
==============================================================================
TimeOfDay - Hour / Minute / Second / Nanosecond Wall-Clock Time
==============================================================================

A TimeOfDay value represents the time-of-day component of a wall-clock
timestamp, decoupled from any calendar date. Range:
  hour       : 0..23
  minute     : 0..59
  second     : 0..60   (60 admits the leap-second instant per
                        ITU-R TF.460-6 §3 and POSIX struct tm convention)
  nanosecond : 0..999_999_999

Internal representation: a single Integer holding the count of
nanoseconds since 00:00:00.000_000_000. Normal range fits in
[0, 86_400_000_000_000); a leap-second instant occupies [86_400e9,
86_401e9). The compact integer representation gives O(1) arithmetic
and trivial comparison.

References:
  ISO 8601-1:2019 §3.5 (time of day, extended format hh:mm:ss[.fff])
  ITU-R TF.460-6 (leap second insertion at 23:59:60 UTC)
  IEEE Std 1003.1-2017 (POSIX) §A.4.16 (struct timespec tv_nsec range)
  RFC 3339 §5.6 (full-time ABNF)
==============================================================================
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Layout and conversion constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TIME_OF_DAY_SIZE_BYTES as Integer is 8
Constant TIME_OF_DAY_OFFSET as Integer is 0

Constant TOD_NS_PER_S as Integer is 1000000000
Constant TOD_NS_PER_MIN as Integer is 60000000000
Constant TOD_NS_PER_HOUR as Integer is 3600000000000

Constant TOD_OK as Integer is 0
Constant TOD_ERR_NULL as Integer is -1
Constant TOD_ERR_INVALID_HOUR as Integer is -2
Constant TOD_ERR_INVALID_MINUTE as Integer is -3
Constant TOD_ERR_INVALID_SECOND as Integer is -4
Constant TOD_ERR_INVALID_NANO as Integer is -5
Constant TOD_ERR_PARSE as Integer is -6

Constant TOD_ASCII_ZERO as Integer is 48
Constant TOD_ASCII_COLON as Integer is 58
Constant TOD_ASCII_DOT as Integer is 46

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Validation
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "time_of_day_validate" takes hour as Integer, minute as Integer, second as Integer, nanosecond as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns TOD_OK iff all four components are inside their permitted
    ranges. Second = 60 is explicitly permitted to support leap-second
    instants; callers that want strict 0..59 seconds should add an
    extra check or use a wrapping arithmetic path.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Four range checks; first-failure short-circuit.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Eight compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If hour is less than 0:
        Return TOD_ERR_INVALID_HOUR
    End If
    If hour is greater than 23:
        Return TOD_ERR_INVALID_HOUR
    End If
    If minute is less than 0:
        Return TOD_ERR_INVALID_MINUTE
    End If
    If minute is greater than 59:
        Return TOD_ERR_INVALID_MINUTE
    End If
    If second is less than 0:
        Return TOD_ERR_INVALID_SECOND
    End If
    If second is greater than 60:
        Return TOD_ERR_INVALID_SECOND
    End If
    If nanosecond is less than 0:
        Return TOD_ERR_INVALID_NANO
    End If
    If nanosecond is greater than 999999999:
        Return TOD_ERR_INVALID_NANO
    End If
    Return TOD_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Allocation / construction
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "time_of_day_allocate" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Reserves an 8-byte TimeOfDay buffer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Layout.allocate.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single tier-3 alloc.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller must release with time_of_day_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc allocate from Layout with TIME_OF_DAY_SIZE_BYTES
End Process

Process called "time_of_day_free" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Releases a TimeOfDay buffer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Layout.deallocate; null is a no-op.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single tier-3 free.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Standard heap rules.
    @End Security_Scope
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TOD_OK
    End If
    Let dummy be proc deallocate from Layout with t
    Return TOD_OK
End Process

Process called "time_of_day_create" takes hour as Integer, minute as Integer, second as Integer, nanosecond as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Builds a new TimeOfDay from the four components. Validates the
    triple, allocates, and packs into the nanosecond representation.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    total_ns = hour * NS_PER_HOUR + minute * NS_PER_MIN +
               second * NS_PER_S + nanosecond
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Validation + four multiplies + three adds + one alloc.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returned pointer must be released with time_of_day_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let v be time_of_day_validate(hour, minute, second, nanosecond)
    If v is not equal to TOD_OK:
        Return v
    End If
    Let total_ns be hour multiplied by TOD_NS_PER_HOUR
    Set total_ns to total_ns plus (minute multiplied by TOD_NS_PER_MIN)
    Set total_ns to total_ns plus (second multiplied by TOD_NS_PER_S)
    Set total_ns to total_ns plus nanosecond
    Let t_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with TIME_OF_DAY_SIZE_BYTES
    If t_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return TOD_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with t_ptr, TIME_OF_DAY_OFFSET, total_ns
    Return t_ptr
End Process

Process called "time_of_day_from_nanoseconds" takes total_ns as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constructs a TimeOfDay from a raw nanosecond count. Used by
    datetime conversions where the packed representation is already
    in hand.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocate and store.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One alloc + one store.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    No range check; caller is responsible for staying within the
    valid range.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let t_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with TIME_OF_DAY_SIZE_BYTES
    If t_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return TOD_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with t_ptr, TIME_OF_DAY_OFFSET, total_ns
    Return t_ptr
End Process

Process called "time_of_day_to_nanoseconds" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Reads the packed nanosecond count.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single load.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with t, TIME_OF_DAY_OFFSET
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Component accessors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "time_of_day_get_hour" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the hour component [0, 23] (or 23 for a leap-second
    instant within the final minute).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Integer-divides the packed nanosecond count by NS_PER_HOUR.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One load + one divide.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ns be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with t, TIME_OF_DAY_OFFSET
    Return ns divided by TOD_NS_PER_HOUR
End Process

Process called "time_of_day_get_minute" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the minute component [0, 59].
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    (ns / NS_PER_MIN) modulo 60.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One load + one divide + one modulo.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ns be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with t, TIME_OF_DAY_OFFSET
    Return (ns divided by TOD_NS_PER_MIN) modulo by 60
End Process

Process called "time_of_day_get_second" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the second component [0, 60]. The value 60 only occurs
    during a positive leap-second insertion at 23:59:60.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    (ns / NS_PER_S) modulo 60, with a leap-second branch when
    ns >= 86_400e9.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One load + one divide + one modulo.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ns be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with t, TIME_OF_DAY_OFFSET
    Note: 86_400 seconds in nanoseconds == 86_400_000_000_000
    If ns is greater than or equal to 86400000000000:
        Return 60
    End If
    Return (ns divided by TOD_NS_PER_S) modulo by 60
End Process

Process called "time_of_day_get_nanosecond" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the fractional-second component [0, 999_999_999].
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    ns modulo NS_PER_S.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One load + one modulo.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ns be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with t, TIME_OF_DAY_OFFSET
    Return ns modulo by TOD_NS_PER_S
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Arithmetic
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "time_of_day_add_nanoseconds" takes t as Integer, delta_ns as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Adds delta_ns to a TimeOfDay, wrapping at midnight per the ISO
    8601 §5.3.1 convention that 24:00:00 is also 00:00:00 of the
    following day. The wrap is modular over the 86_400_000_000_000 ns
    interval; callers tracking day rollover must consult the
    DateTime layer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Adds, then applies a modular reduction. Returns a fresh
    TimeOfDay.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One add + one modulo + one alloc.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returned pointer must be released with time_of_day_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TOD_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let ns be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with t, TIME_OF_DAY_OFFSET
    Let new_ns be ns plus delta_ns
    Let day_span be 86400000000000
    Let wrapped be new_ns modulo by day_span
    If wrapped is less than 0:
        Set wrapped to wrapped plus day_span
    End If
    Return time_of_day_from_nanoseconds(wrapped)
End Process

Process called "time_of_day_diff_nanoseconds" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the signed nanosecond difference (a - b). Useful for
    computing the elapsed time-of-day between two readings within
    the same calendar day.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Subtracts the packed nanosecond counts.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two loads + one subtract.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let an be time_of_day_to_nanoseconds(a)
    Let bn be time_of_day_to_nanoseconds(b)
    Return an minus bn
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Comparison
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "time_of_day_compare" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Three-way compare on the packed nanosecond representation.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Subtracts and signs to -1 / 0 / +1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two loads + one subtract.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let an be time_of_day_to_nanoseconds(a)
    Let bn be time_of_day_to_nanoseconds(b)
    If an is less than bn:
        Return -1
    End If
    If an is greater than bn:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "time_of_day_equals" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Equality predicate.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    time_of_day_compare returns 0.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same as time_of_day_compare.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If time_of_day_compare(a, b) is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ISO 8601 formatting
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "_tod_write_2digit" takes buf as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes a 2-digit zero-padded representation of an integer in
    [0, 99].
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Tens + units.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two divides + two stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Bounded write of 2 bytes.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let t be value divided by 10
    Let u be value modulo by 10
    Let off0 be offset
    Let off1 be offset plus 1
    Let d0 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off0, t plus TOD_ASCII_ZERO
    Let d1 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off1, u plus TOD_ASCII_ZERO
    Return 2
End Process

Process called "_tod_write_9digit" takes buf as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes nine zero-padded digits of an integer in
    [0, 999_999_999]. Used to format the fractional-second component
    in ISO 8601 §3.5.4 output.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Walks high-to-low through powers of ten.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Nine divides + nine stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Bounded write of 9 bytes.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let divisor be 100000000
    Let v be value
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 9:
        Let digit be v divided by divisor
        Let pos be offset plus i
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, pos, digit plus TOD_ASCII_ZERO
        Set v to v modulo by divisor
        Set divisor to divisor divided by 10
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 9
End Process

Process called "time_of_day_to_iso_8601" takes t as Integer, out_buf as Integer, out_capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emits the ISO 8601 §3.5.3 extended representation
    "hh:mm:ss" with an optional ".fffffffff" fractional-second
    appendix when the nanosecond field is non-zero. Trailing zeros
    in the fractional part are trimmed per RFC 3339 implementations.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reads h, m, s, ns from the packed representation, writes the
    three two-digit fields separated by colons, then appends the
    fractional-second portion if non-zero.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(output length).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Bounded write: 8 bytes minimum, 18 bytes maximum.
    @End Security_Scope
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return TOD_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return TOD_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If out_capacity is less than 8:
        Return TOD_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let hour_val be time_of_day_get_hour(t)
    Let minute_val be time_of_day_get_minute(t)
    Let second_val be time_of_day_get_second(t)
    Let ns_val be time_of_day_get_nanosecond(t)
    Let cursor be 0
    Let hlen be _tod_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, hour_val)
    Set cursor to cursor plus hlen
    Let dummy_c1 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, TOD_ASCII_COLON
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let mlen be _tod_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, minute_val)
    Set cursor to cursor plus mlen
    Let dummy_c2 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, TOD_ASCII_COLON
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let slen be _tod_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, second_val)
    Set cursor to cursor plus slen
    If ns_val is greater than 0:
        Let dummy_dot be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, TOD_ASCII_DOT
        Set cursor to cursor plus 1
        Let dlen be _tod_write_9digit(out_buf, cursor, ns_val)
        Note: Trim trailing zeros (in-place by inspecting from the right).
        Let trim be 0
        Let scan_pos be (cursor plus dlen) minus 1
        While scan_pos is greater than cursor:
            Let c be proc memory_get_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, scan_pos
            If c is equal to TOD_ASCII_ZERO:
                Set trim to trim plus 1
                Set scan_pos to scan_pos minus 1
            Otherwise:
                Set scan_pos to cursor
            End If
        End While
        Set cursor to (cursor plus dlen) minus trim
    End If
    Return cursor
End Process

Process called "_tod_parse_uint" takes input as Integer, start as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parses 'length' ASCII digits into an unsigned integer; returns
    -1 on any non-digit.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Left-to-right accumulation.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(length).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller ensures the input has 'length' bytes available.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let result be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let pos be start plus i
        Let c be proc memory_get_int8 from MemoryCore with input, pos
        If c is less than TOD_ASCII_ZERO:
            Return -1
        End If
        If c is greater than 57:
            Return -1
        End If
        Set result to (result multiplied by 10) plus (c minus TOD_ASCII_ZERO)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Process called "time_of_day_parse_iso_8601" takes input as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parses an ISO 8601 §3.5.3 extended-format time string
    "hh:mm:ss[.fff...]". Returns a TimeOfDay pointer on success,
    TOD_ERR_PARSE on malformed input.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Verifies the two colon positions, parses h / m / s, then if a
    decimal point exists at offset 8 parses the fractional digits as
    a nanosecond pad. Up to 9 fractional digits are honoured; any
    additional digits are truncated (RFC 3339 implementations are
    free to do either, we choose truncation for determinism).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three small parses + optional fractional parse.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller supplies length; we honour it strictly to prevent reads
    past the end of the input buffer.
    @End Security_Scope
    If input is equal to 0:
        Return TOD_ERR_PARSE
    End If
    If length is less than 8:
        Return TOD_ERR_PARSE
    End If
    Let c1 be proc memory_get_int8 from MemoryCore with input, 2
    Let c2 be proc memory_get_int8 from MemoryCore with input, 5
    If c1 is not equal to TOD_ASCII_COLON:
        Return TOD_ERR_PARSE
    End If
    If c2 is not equal to TOD_ASCII_COLON:
        Return TOD_ERR_PARSE
    End If
    Let h be _tod_parse_uint(input, 0, 2)
    Let m be _tod_parse_uint(input, 3, 2)
    Let s be _tod_parse_uint(input, 6, 2)
    If h is less than 0:
        Return TOD_ERR_PARSE
    End If
    If m is less than 0:
        Return TOD_ERR_PARSE
    End If
    If s is less than 0:
        Return TOD_ERR_PARSE
    End If
    Let ns_part be 0
    If length is greater than 9:
        Let dot be proc memory_get_int8 from MemoryCore with input, 8
        If dot is equal to TOD_ASCII_DOT:
            Note: Parse up to 9 fractional digits.
            Let frac_start be 9
            Let frac_index be 0
            Let multiplier be 100000000
            While frac_index is less than 9:
                Let pos be frac_start plus frac_index
                If pos is greater than or equal to length:
                    Set frac_index to 9
                Otherwise:
                    Let cf be proc memory_get_int8 from MemoryCore with input, pos
                    If cf is less than TOD_ASCII_ZERO:
                        Set frac_index to 9
                    Otherwise:
                        If cf is greater than 57:
                            Set frac_index to 9
                        Otherwise:
                            Set ns_part to ns_part plus ((cf minus TOD_ASCII_ZERO) multiplied by multiplier)
                            Set multiplier to multiplier divided by 10
                            Set frac_index to frac_index plus 1
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If
    Return time_of_day_create(h, m, s, ns_part)
End Process
